text.text: The closest youâ€™ll get to seaside living without leaving London, Wapping takes advantage of prime riverside frontage, spacious warehouse buildings and a historic past. Before we have you reaching for your pepper spray because you think we're estate agents, here are our favourite places to have it large.

tip.text: A bit of a favourite among Wapping locals, Cinnamon is a cosy little cafe with mismatched furniture that does the things a cafe does and does them well. That means tea, coffee and smoothies alongside a food menu of homemade cakes, vegetarian savoury bits and soups and sandwiches. Keep an eye out for that gingerbread latte if you wanna spice things up a bit. It's a free WiFi situation, and the place is primed to get extremely cosy - perfect for letting time slip by when you should be doing something more important.

listing.name: Emilia's Crafted Pasta - St Katherine's Dock
listing.subtitle: Fresh Pasta Bar

tip.text:
Amidst all the very average chain restaurants on the beautiful St Katharine's Docks there's one definite gem: Emilia's. This is a lovely little hub of Italian cuisine where the pasta is crafted in the kitchen and then covered in delicious, oozing homemade sauces. It's rich, it's creamy, and it hits the spot of indulgence that you really ought to be hitting more often.

They want you to take your time with it here - we recommend sitting back and indulging over a couple of hours with their burrata and toasted ciabatta, slow-cooked bÃ©chamel bolognese with grated parmesan, or flaked yellowfin tuna fillet with peperoncino and tomato sauce. Sit outside (if the weather permits) and imagine you're a high roller on the Amalfi Coast. A bit of escapism and Italian gratification.

text.text: This little Italian hub overlooking St Katharine's Docks is all about making really wholesome, carb-filled, fresh-as-fuck pasta and covering it in delicious, oozing homemade sauces. Think creamy walnut sauce with chestnut mushrooms, slow-cooked bÃ©chamel bolognese with grated parmesan, or flaked yellowfin tuna fillet with peperoncino and tomato sauce. Then start thinking about who's going to order an Uber, because homemade pasta + five Negronis = naptime, asap.
Best for... moody cocktails and a gig

tip.text:
Think you've seen it all, and drunk in it all? Wilton's Music Hall is the oldest Victorian music hall to survive anywhere in the world. It's grand, shabby-chic, and pretty damn beautiful. Not only can you come see a show here, but also have a cocktail mixed up in style too.

The Mahogany Bar here actually dates back to 1690 and feels its age, but in a good way. The cocktails stick to the classic recipes, and you can get takeaway ordered in to your table. Everyone should come here at least once.

Best for... pretending youâ€™re on your holidays

tip.text:
Perched on the edge of the Thames with a pebbly beach, a hangman's pole and the finest views that anyone did see, a trip to The Prospect of Whitby is as close to a holiday as you're going to get in London.

Apparently it's one of London's oldest pubs so there's plenty of character and if you're not so fussed with character, they also serve a solid selection of cask ales, perfect for enjoying on the terrace. On the food menu are all the classics. Nothing's going to rock your world but the Sausage and Mash should fill a hole.

text.text: Perched on the edge of the Thames with a pebbly beach, a hangman's pole and the finest views that anyone did see, a trip to The Prospect of Whitby is as close to a holiday as you're going to get in London. It's one of London's oldest public houses, so expect the cask ales they do here to come with a large side of character.

tip.text:
They say you gotta play to your strengths, and thereâ€™s no doubting that Bravas Tapasâ€™ main strength is location. Overlooking the lapping harbour of St. Katharine Docks - aka the London riviera - it's one of the only independent restaurants in this chain-ridden patch and it does a pretty reasonable job of Spanish escapism. It combines a rustic, if slightly try-hard, feel with decent tapas fodder and a much in-demand terrace on those sunny days.

For the feeding, we're talking typical tapas dishes with a slight Basque influence. You've got those bravas, Padron peppers, grilled octopus, moorish spiced lamb chops, seared mediterranean sea bass fillet - all present, all correct. It's a pretty social place capable of getting loud and lively - particularly when the cocktails begin to flow and the imagination takes you to a dockside restaurant in Valencia, or suchlike.

text.text: Bravas Tapas definitely takes advantage of its location and who can blame it. Bring a date here, because sharing from their flawless tapas selection on their terrace while overlooking the St Katherine's Dock Marina is what romance is all about. Go for the spiced lamb chops with rosemary alioli, the fresh salmon rulada and the spinach croquetas.

tip.text: Why do things in halves when you can go large scale? That's the ethos behind Skylight, with two levels of street food, cocktails and traditional British lawn games. You can book one of the three croquet lawns and two pÃ©tanque courts, challenge the most pompous of your friends and prove yourself completely inadequate in the hand-eye coordination department. Then drown your sorrows with the comforting combination of Aperol spritz and salty street-food snacks. Nibble on burgers, bibimbaps or pittas stuffed full of the good stuff. Now to check the weather forecast...

Then drown your sorrows with the comforting combination of spritz and burgers from We Serve Humans. Happy (and sunny) days.

tip.text:
Looking out over St. Katherine's Docks in the only remaining original warehouse still there, this water-front independent cafe is a real picturesque place. In many ways it fits the hidden gem criteria - a minimalist and friendly venue which you'd only really come across if you knew what you were looking for.

Run by husband and wife Peyman and Rana, it does very good coffee alongside home-made cakes and some snacks. It's not a large space, but if you manage to nab a seat out front it offers a very tranquil setting for a cup of joe. It also won the prestigious London's Best Coffee Shop award in 2014 - which is what every coffee place in town hopes to achieve, deep down.

text.text: Looking out over St. Katherine's Docks, this independent waterfront cafe couldn't be more picturesque. Whether you're strolling by on a weekend or stopping by for a work meeting, it's ideal for expertly made coffee, homemade cakes and savoury snacks.
Best for... getting it on till the early morn

tip.text:
Party Berlin style in this Wapping great warehouse. Home to underground, electronic party collective The Hydra, it serves as a space for some of London's finest electronic sessions.

During the day the space is used as a photographic studio and it's been known to host a few other events too.
